included.description: Using advanced statistical methods and semi-structured interviews my research examined the psychological mechanisms underlying the relationship between varying types of xenophobic behavior and political engagement. The theoretical contribution took an interdisciplinary approach, drawing from political science, social psychology, and sociology, to examine how increased anti-immigrant and Islamophobic rhetoric and hostility affects the political attitudes and behavior of visible minorities, such as individuals with a migration background and Muslims, in Western democracies, using Germany as the primary case study.

included.description:
As part of my PhD training, I designed university-level introductory courses (PS1200: Introduction to Comparative Politics) using an online learning management system (Carmen) to facilitate discussions and feedback. For several semesters, I have worked in tandem with Prof. Sarah Brooks to teach large-scale online courses, where my primary goal was to implement course objectives and maintain organization of course documents and assignments. As a graduate TA, I facilitate communication between students and Prof. Brooks, as well as between students themselves through online discussion forums. One method I use to incorporate current affairs and encourage communication is a weekly media discussion forum, wherein students update each other on happenings throughout the world. 

Prior to teaching online, I conceptualized, designed, and taught upper-level general education course on political extremism and right-wing movements in Europe (PS 4792.02: Topics in Contemporary Politics, Autumn 2014). For this course, I worked one-on-one with students and guided their research on self-selected topics relating to political extremism.
included.title: Graduate Teaching Assistant

included.description: As a data scientist contractor in the Marketing Department in the Customer Insight and Analytics division, I synthesized enterprise, customer, corporate, and publicly available data to identify and generate insight for future marketing decisions at Nationwide. While there I updated existing market assessment project to reflect current socio-economic and demographic indicators that can influence business decision making. Also, in order to take advantage of the diversity in backgrounds and skill sets on our team, I worked with my team director to develop bi-weekly project focused round tables where team members could "shop" their projects, get feedback, brainstorm ideas, and trouble shoot problems.
included.title: Data Scientist (Contractor)

included.description: I work with authors, editors, and publishers to update and design supplementary material for comparative politics and international relations textbooks. This works requires not only that I stay up-to-date with current events, but also immersed in recent and upcoming academic works. I also design the course material so that it is easily adapted for both in-class and online courses.
included.title: Freelance Consultant

included.description: For my dissertation, I planned, managed, and implemented three year research project examining the psychological and political effects of hate crimes on immigrants in Germany. For this research, I raised $25,000 to conduct 10 months of hands-on research in Germany while contributing as a guest researcher at the German Institute for Economic Research and the Social Science Research Center in Berlin. While in Germany, I conducted face-to-face interviews and evaluated 30,000+ news articles to qualitatively explore the development of xenophobia and crimes since reunification (1990). Since data on hate crime distribution is unavailable in Germany, I organized and implemented collection of >10,000 parliamentary inquiries from 16 regional archives to produce unique data set on crimes against immigrants and minorities in Germany between 2006 and 2016 (to be released for public use in Spring 2017). Finally, to understand the psychological mechanisms underlying reaction to hate crimes, I designed and conducted survey experiment of immigrant and hard-to-reach populations in Germany to determine effects of short-term exposure to various levels and types of threats.

As a newly minted Ph.D. and recovering academic, I've transitioned to the non-academic world, using my speciality in research design and project planning to help uncover insights and provide feedback on products as a user experience researcher at OCLC.  

In my free time, I'm usually running in the woods, completing marathons & 50Ks, getting lost in the mountains, building things, or working in the yard.
